  "doc_id": "35718",
  "text": "There was no statistical correlation between mucosal bacterial sub-populations in the ileum and colon and the CIBDAI or histopathology score in IBD dogs and dogs with GC. This finding may have been due to the fact that we evaluated only the number of attaching/invading bacteria, versus mucus-laden bacteria, in canine cohorts having mucosal inflammation. This could also be influenced by the small study size (especially in GC dogs), the contribution from non-bacterial factors mediating GI disease (ie, local immune response, motility disturbances), and/or the difficulties inherent in the histopathologic interpretation of endoscopic biopsies [CITATION_1] . In spite of these factors, we did observe a significant positive correlation between the number of total bacteria attached to the colonic mucosa and the CIBDAI score in IBD dogs having moderate-to-severe disease severity.",
